💿 Option 2: Use the Live ISO (may require boot parameter tweaks)

We built a bootable ISO from the chroot:

/home/aegon/lilith-linux-1.0-cubic.iso   (≈2.7GB)
To test it in a VM:

# Create a 30GB disk image (if not already exists)
qemu-img create -f qcow2 /home/aegon/vms/lilith-test.qcow2 30G

# Start the VM
qemu-system-x86_64 \
  -m 4096 \
  -smp 2 \
  -cdrom /home/aegon/lilith-linux-1.0-cubic.iso \
  -drive file=/home/aegon/vms/lilith-test.qcow2,format=qcow2 \
  -boot d \
  -nic user,model=virtio-net-pci \
  -display gtk \
  -name "Lilith Linux Test" &
If the VM kernel panics, try adjusting the GRUB boot parameters (edit at the GRUB screen by pressing e):

Remove quiet splash to see verbose output
Try boot=casper live-media-path=/casper
Try adding break=top or break=mount to get a busybox shell when it fails
Try nomodeset if you suspect graphics issues
🌐 Option 3: Transform a fresh Pop!OS/Ubuntu 24.04 system into Lilith Linux (single script)

If you prefer to install Lilith Linux directly onto hardware or into a VM via a fresh Pop!OS/Ubuntu install, use the all-in-one transformation script:

wget -O install-lilith-host.sh https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BlancoBAM/Lilith-Build/master/install-lilith-host.sh
chmod +x install-lilith-host.sh
sudo ./install-lilith-host.sh
This script will:

Update the base system
Add the Pop!OS repository (for COSMIC)
Install COSMIC desktop and essential packages
Install Hyper 3.4.1 (AppImage)
Install Rust and the full Rust tooling from lil-staRS.toml
Replace GNU coreutils with uutils (symlinks in /usr/local/bin)
Install Lilith custom apps (where source is available)
Apply Lilith branding (os-release, issue, LightDM)
Install Fluent-icon-theme (dark)
Install Flatpak and Snap apps from lil-pax.toml
Configure topgrade (s8n upd8 for updates)
Create the lilith user (password: lilith)
Clean up caches
After it finishes, reboot (or start the desktop with startx) and log in as user lilith with password lilith.

